1
00:00:15,182 --> 00:00:16,683
Next, please.

2
00:00:17,268 --> 00:00:18,643
Come on, come on.

3
00:00:19,103 --> 00:00:20,270
Next.

4
00:00:20,646 --> 00:00:21,771
Name.

5
00:00:21,939 --> 00:00:23,648
Gus Gorman.

6
00:00:31,449 --> 00:00:33,783
Ah, yes. August Gorman.

7
00:00:33,951 --> 00:00:36,244
Have you looked for work this week?

8
00:00:36,787 --> 00:00:39,164
- Yes.
- What kind?

9
00:00:41,417 --> 00:00:44,294
- Kitchen technician.
- Dishwasher. Any luck?

10
00:00:45,171 --> 00:00:46,212
No, but...

11
00:00:46,380 --> 00:00:50,091
Mr. Gorman, according to our records,
you've been unemployed for 36 weeks.

12
00:00:50,301 --> 00:00:51,426
No, it's 35.

13
00:00:51,594 --> 00:00:53,470
Not counting this week.

14
00:00:53,721 --> 00:00:58,099
You secured employment in June as
a messenger and were discharged after...

15
00:00:58,267 --> 00:01:01,061
- one day for losing...
- No, they said I lost it.

16
00:01:01,270 --> 00:01:04,314
I did not lose it!
It was stolen by a pickpocket.

17
00:01:04,482 --> 00:01:05,940
A television set?

18
00:01:06,192 --> 00:01:09,819
It was a teeny-tiny, teeny-weensy
Japanese television set.

19
00:01:09,987 --> 00:01:14,949
The other employment you found
was in a fast-food joint, which lasted...

20
00:01:15,159 --> 00:01:16,493
28 minutes?

21
00:01:16,994 --> 00:01:19,329
That's some kind of record.
Talk about fast.

22
00:01:19,580 --> 00:01:24,084
Those people are crazy. They expect
you to learn that stuff in one day.

23
00:01:24,293 --> 00:01:28,254
"Hold the lettuce. Hold the ketchup.
Can I have some sauce, please?"

24
00:01:28,464 --> 00:01:31,007
- Mr. Gorman...
- "Two buns. No buns. Some cheese".

25
00:01:31,342 --> 00:01:34,719
Mr. Gorman, the city of Metropolis
is generous to a fault, but...

26
00:01:35,012 --> 00:01:36,096
I'm not the fault!

27
00:01:36,263 --> 00:01:38,181
Thirty-six weeks
of chronic unemployment.

28
00:01:38,349 --> 00:01:41,518
Thirty-six weeks of living off the taxes
of hard-working citizens.

29
00:01:41,727 --> 00:01:44,979
- Do you know what you are?
- Don't call me a bum, I'm not a bum!

30
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:50,819
You are, I was about to say,
no longer eligible.

31
00:01:51,445 --> 00:01:52,862
- Well, look...
- Next.

32
00:01:53,030 --> 00:01:55,156
Wait. What about this week?
I need this week!

33
00:01:55,533 --> 00:01:56,616
Next.

34
00:01:56,951 --> 00:01:58,535
You mean, that's it?

35
00:01:58,869 --> 00:02:00,745
"Finished," like "over"?

36
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:05,750
Next.

37
00:02:06,377 --> 00:02:08,253
"Next" as in "bye".

38
00:02:09,004 --> 00:02:10,255
Next!

39
00:02:13,259 --> 00:02:14,342
Name.

40
00:02:16,053 --> 00:02:18,054
Excuse me, brother,
can I have a light?

41
00:02:48,711 --> 00:02:50,920
- How you doing, Alex?
- Hi, Jimmy.

42
00:04:48,706 --> 00:04:49,914
Excuse me.

43
00:06:05,199 --> 00:06:06,616
Say thank you.

44
00:06:06,784 --> 00:06:08,368
Wow!

45
00:06:25,636 --> 00:06:27,970
Way to go, Superman!

46
00:07:43,714 --> 00:07:45,882
Your drink is on its way.

47
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:48,551
Sir.

48
00:07:48,719 --> 00:07:50,303
Excuse me...

49
00:07:52,306 --> 00:07:57,018
but what if you wanna program two
bilateral coordinates at the same time?

50
00:07:57,227 --> 00:07:59,228
You can't do that. It's impossible.

51
00:07:59,396 --> 00:08:01,147
- But if you can't...
- Oh, no.

52
00:08:01,356 --> 00:08:05,401
Computer technology is very advanced,
young lady, but it can't do that.

53
00:08:05,611 --> 00:08:08,571
But if you think we can't
do it that way, what happens?

54
00:08:08,739 --> 00:08:10,364
Sir.

55
00:08:15,579 --> 00:08:16,913
Good Lord.

56
00:08:17,498 --> 00:08:18,915
How did you do that?

57
00:08:19,124 --> 00:08:22,710
I don't know. I just did it.

58
00:08:41,730 --> 00:08:44,232
- Who's this?
- That's him, Ross Webster.

59
00:08:44,441 --> 00:08:47,443
Just after he received the award for
Humanitarian of the Year.

60
00:08:47,611 --> 00:08:49,362
He is good-looking.

61
00:08:49,571 --> 00:08:51,447
Because I gave him F2 at a 50th.

62
00:08:51,698 --> 00:08:53,449
One thing I don't understand...

63
00:08:53,659 --> 00:08:57,954
the point of the story Lois wrote
is how Ross got this great honor...

64
00:08:58,121 --> 00:09:01,791
and you bring me one picture of him
and 15 pictures of this other person.

65
00:09:01,959 --> 00:09:04,627
- Who is she?
- Lorelei Ambrosia. She's Webster's...

66
00:09:04,795 --> 00:09:07,463
She's just Webster's.
Let's leave it at that.

67
00:09:07,673 --> 00:09:10,299
- Who's this other woman?
- His sister, Vera Webster.

68
00:09:10,467 --> 00:09:11,801
- Picture looks fuzzy.
- What?

69
00:09:11,969 --> 00:09:15,763
The picture's fine, chief.
She looks like that in real life.

70
00:09:16,306 --> 00:09:20,184
- She's VP of Webscoe Industries.
- I really don't understand you.

71
00:09:20,394 --> 00:09:23,688
A boring banquet and you bring me
3000 boring pictures.

72
00:09:23,897 --> 00:09:26,649
Yet Superman saves a man
from drowning on Third Avenue...

73
00:09:26,817 --> 00:09:30,236
while you just stand there and
you don't bring me one picture!

74
00:09:30,404 --> 00:09:32,238
Chief, I didn't have
my camera with me.

75
00:09:32,447 --> 00:09:36,826
A photographer eats with his camera.
A photographer sleeps with his camera.

76
00:09:36,994 --> 00:09:39,453
- I'm glad I'm a writer.
- Mr. White, please.

77
00:09:39,663 --> 00:09:42,832
It's time for you to draw this month's
winning JINGO number.

78
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,585
Prize is an all-expenses trip
to South America.

79
00:09:45,752 --> 00:09:48,588
- I don't know why the idiot in Circulation...
- Good morning.

80
00:09:48,755 --> 00:09:50,798
- Hi, Clark.
- Hi, Lois. Morning, Jimmy.

81
00:09:51,008 --> 00:09:52,758
You've got mustard on your lapel.

82
00:09:52,968 --> 00:09:54,969
Excuse me, Mr. White,
I hate to interrupt...

83
00:09:55,178 --> 00:09:57,430
Sorry. I'm busy.
I got a paper to get out here.

84
00:09:57,639 --> 00:09:59,682
It'll never replace the printing press.

85
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:02,852
- What's the number, Mr. White?
- Fifty-three.

86
00:10:04,354 --> 00:10:07,023
- Mr. White...
- Fifty-three!

87
00:10:07,649 --> 00:10:10,693
- Mr. White...
- You've got to pull three more numbers.

88
00:10:10,861 --> 00:10:13,654
I promised I'd call them back today.
What do you think?

89
00:10:14,197 --> 00:10:17,867
- Well, I don't know, Kent...
- I think it'd make a terrific story.

90
00:10:19,036 --> 00:10:20,703
What's a terrific story?

91
00:10:20,871 --> 00:10:23,247
Kent's been invited
to his high-school reunion.

92
00:10:23,707 --> 00:10:25,207
- Say.
- Yeah.

93
00:10:25,375 --> 00:10:27,209
Could we have the next number?

94
00:10:27,377 --> 00:10:29,879
It's practically an
American institution. Isn't it?

95
00:10:30,047 --> 00:10:34,008
I don't know, Mr. Kent. Most of
the people I know are still in high school.

96
00:10:37,554 --> 00:10:38,638
Thirty-three.

97
00:10:38,805 --> 00:10:41,557
What I thought this story
would be about, Mr. White, is...

98
00:10:41,767 --> 00:10:43,392
Thirty-three.

99
00:10:43,894 --> 00:10:47,396
Is how much the typical small town
has changed in the last 15 years.

100
00:10:47,648 --> 00:10:48,773
Take me, for example:

101
00:10:48,982 --> 00:10:52,652
Can I really go back to middle America
now as a Metropolis sophisticate?

102
00:10:52,819 --> 00:10:55,821
I'm really excited about this.
In fact, I was looking around...

103
00:10:56,031 --> 00:10:58,491
in my closet last night...

104
00:10:58,700 --> 00:11:02,536
and I even found
my old high-school sweater.

105
00:11:04,831 --> 00:11:06,916
- Smallville.
- Mr. White.

106
00:11:07,584 --> 00:11:09,585
Can I go ahead
and make my travel plan?

107
00:11:09,795 --> 00:11:11,295
Same question about mine.

108
00:11:12,172 --> 00:11:15,925
Tell your people the prodigal son
and his photographer are coming home.

109
00:11:16,093 --> 00:11:17,927
Oh, gee, thanks, Mr. White.

110
00:11:19,846 --> 00:11:23,099
It isn't easy for me to lose
one of my best reporters.

111
00:11:23,308 --> 00:11:25,685
- That's okay.
- You deserve the vacation, Lois.

112
00:11:25,894 --> 00:11:27,103
Thank you.

113
00:11:29,773 --> 00:11:31,232
Lois, are you going some place?

114
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:36,112
Clark, you know some people
get to go all the way to Smallville...

115
00:11:36,279 --> 00:11:40,074
and then there are others of us
who have to go to Bermuda.

116
00:11:40,575 --> 00:11:41,909
Golly.

117
00:11:42,119 --> 00:11:43,452
- Bye.
- Bye, Miss Lane.

118
00:11:44,955 --> 00:11:48,958
- Have fun.
- Mr. White, the next number, please.

119
00:11:49,126 --> 00:11:52,128
Well, I guess I better be going too.

120
00:11:54,089 --> 00:11:55,756
So I'll be going.

121
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:00,219
Bye.

122
00:12:02,639 --> 00:12:04,807
Couldn't we get a computer to do this?

123
00:12:28,165 --> 00:12:30,875
- Hey, what is this?
- First paycheck.

124
00:12:31,293 --> 00:12:35,504
This is the first rip-off, man! We're
supposed to get 225 a week, right?

125
00:12:35,672 --> 00:12:38,966
This says, "$143.80".
How am I supposed to live on that?

126
00:12:39,176 --> 00:12:42,470
State tax, federal tax,
social security tax...

127
00:12:42,637 --> 00:12:45,306
It's so you're still getting
some money when you hit 65.

128
00:12:45,474 --> 00:12:47,683
So I'm getting money when I? 65?

129
00:12:47,934 --> 00:12:49,185
I want mine now!

130
00:12:49,394 --> 00:12:53,898
I want to enjoy it while I'm young.
I wanna get up and get down. Boogie.

131
00:12:55,400 --> 00:13:00,196
Actually, it's probably more like
$143.80 and one half cent.

132
00:13:00,405 --> 00:13:04,700
There are always fractions left over,
but big corporations round it down.

133
00:13:04,951 --> 00:13:07,703
What do I do with half a cent?
Buy a thoroughbred mouse?

134
00:13:07,913 --> 00:13:09,705
Everybody loses those fractions?

135
00:13:09,956 --> 00:13:12,708
They don't lose them.
You can't lose what you never got.

136
00:13:12,959 --> 00:13:15,127
Then what happens?
The company gets them?

137
00:13:15,337 --> 00:13:19,965
They can't be bothered collecting that
from your paycheck any more than you.

138
00:13:20,217 --> 00:13:21,550
Then what happens to them?

139
00:13:21,843 --> 00:13:26,305
Well, they're just floating around
out there. The computers know where.

140
00:13:26,515 --> 00:13:28,015
How many sugars?

141
00:13:28,725 --> 00:13:30,059
One and a half.

142
00:13:37,442 --> 00:13:39,193
It's quitting time, Gus. You coming?

143
00:13:39,361 --> 00:13:44,031
Yeah. No, actually, I got some
stuff to finish up, so...

144
00:13:44,241 --> 00:13:49,078
Working overtime, huh? What are you
doing, buddy? Looking for a raise?

145
00:13:49,871 --> 00:13:52,248
Yeah, looking for a raise.

146
00:14:29,744 --> 00:14:30,786
You bet.

147
00:14:36,918 --> 00:14:40,629
But my Uncle Al on my father's
side, he won't eat her stuffing.

148
00:14:40,797 --> 00:14:45,467
He says it should be cooked on the outside.
She cooks it on the inside.

149
00:14:45,635 --> 00:14:48,804
My mother told my Aunt Helen.
She's my father's half sister.

150
00:14:48,972 --> 00:14:51,140
- I told you that, right?
- Yeah.

151
00:14:51,308 --> 00:14:53,017
- And anyway, the family...
- Hey, hey.

152
00:14:53,435 --> 00:14:55,311
- Look at that.
- Wow.

153
00:15:06,156 --> 00:15:10,492
Okay, your choice. You can
turn back or pull over till it's over.

154
00:15:10,660 --> 00:15:13,245
- How long will it take?
- Can't tell with these fires.

155
00:15:13,413 --> 00:15:16,498
I mean, that fire...
That's spreading like wildfire.

156
00:15:16,666 --> 00:15:18,167
It's just a building burning.

157
00:15:18,335 --> 00:15:20,669
It's not just a building.
That's a chemical plant.

158
00:15:21,171 --> 00:15:24,465
You know what I mean.
It's like... It's like chemicals.

159
00:15:24,674 --> 00:15:29,303
If any of that stuff goes up in smoke,
we're in for a hairy time around here.

160
00:15:31,181 --> 00:15:32,306
- Clark.
- Yeah?

161
00:15:32,474 --> 00:15:34,683
I want you to keep
these people distracted.

162
00:15:34,851 --> 00:15:36,018
What are you doing?

163
00:15:36,186 --> 00:15:39,313
What am I doing?
Remember what the chief said?

164
00:15:39,481 --> 00:15:41,690
A photographer always
goes after a story.

165
00:15:41,858 --> 00:15:43,442
That could be dangerous, Jimmy.

166
00:15:43,652 --> 00:15:47,696
Danger goes with the territory,
Mr. Kent.

167
00:16:24,234 --> 00:16:27,486
Help me!

168
00:16:31,408 --> 00:16:33,742
- How can I help?
- Get this man a helmet.

169
00:16:33,910 --> 00:16:36,120
- It's you. Forget the helmet.
- How bad is it?

170
00:16:36,329 --> 00:16:40,708
My God, it's a nightmare. Everything's
either explosive or flammable or worse.

171
00:16:44,921 --> 00:16:46,338
Get the ladder truck in here.

172
00:16:46,506 --> 00:16:49,383
- It won't reach.
- My God, they're trapped!

173
00:16:50,135 --> 00:16:52,928
What's he gonna do?
Fly them down one at a time?

174
00:17:11,156 --> 00:17:13,282
Let's go! Everybody,
down there! Move it!

175
00:17:13,533 --> 00:17:15,117
Come on! Hurry up!

176
00:17:15,285 --> 00:17:16,410
There you go.

177
00:17:20,290 --> 00:17:22,166
Right down there. Take it easy.

178
00:17:24,419 --> 00:17:26,253
All right. Everybody down there!

179
00:17:28,298 --> 00:17:29,631
Keep moving!

180
00:18:02,832 --> 00:18:05,000
Sir, get out. I'll show you
the quickest way.

181
00:18:05,210 --> 00:18:07,336
Go on. Look after the others.
I can't leave.

182
00:18:07,504 --> 00:18:09,755
- Why not?
- I gotta stay and look after those.

183
00:18:09,964 --> 00:18:11,507
That's concentrated Beltric acid.

184
00:18:11,716 --> 00:18:14,802
If that stuff heats up over 180 degrees,
we've got a crisis...

185
00:18:15,011 --> 00:18:17,346
that'll make this fire
look like a picnic.

186
00:18:17,514 --> 00:18:18,597
What does it do?

187
00:18:18,848 --> 00:18:21,642
As long as it remains stable,
it's just ordinary acid.

188
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:25,312
But if it begins to heat up,
it'll turn volatile.

189
00:18:25,522 --> 00:18:28,732
You'll get a great cloud of smoke
that will eat through anything.

190
00:18:28,942 --> 00:18:31,527
Steel, concrete, anything.

191
00:18:42,956 --> 00:18:44,164
Who the hell is that?

192
00:18:44,332 --> 00:18:49,169
- Hey, you! Get off of there!
- I'm just gonna get a couple more shots.

193
00:19:05,395 --> 00:19:08,772
Tell them to bring their hoses
back here! Quickly!

194
00:19:11,776 --> 00:19:12,860
Help!

195
00:19:13,695 --> 00:19:16,196
Help! Help me!

196
00:19:18,032 --> 00:19:21,535
Help! Somebody help me!

197
00:19:22,495 --> 00:19:24,079
- Help!
- It's all right.

198
00:19:24,330 --> 00:19:26,915
- Superman! My leg.
- I got you. Take it easy.

199
00:19:27,083 --> 00:19:28,876
All right. We'll go nice and easy.

200
00:19:29,085 --> 00:19:32,880
Okay, I'm sorry.
All right? Here we go.

201
00:19:36,426 --> 00:19:38,927
Medics! Over here, please.

202
00:19:39,554 --> 00:19:41,722
That's it. Here you go.

203
00:19:41,890 --> 00:19:43,432
Go easy. It's the left leg.

204
00:19:44,893 --> 00:19:46,268
- My camera.
- Yeah.

205
00:19:47,729 --> 00:19:49,813
It's a clean break right across the fibula.

206
00:19:50,356 --> 00:19:53,901
- My camera.
- Sorry, Jimmy. You'll be okay.

207
00:19:55,403 --> 00:19:59,823
Get that fire out, otherwise there'll be an
acid cloud all over the Eastern seaboard.

208
00:20:03,912 --> 00:20:06,455
- The pump house is gone!
- What?

209
00:20:06,623 --> 00:20:09,124
- The pump house!
- We've lost the water pressure!

210
00:20:10,835 --> 00:20:12,628
- We've got to have water!
- How?

211
00:20:12,795 --> 00:20:15,797
Lake Comooga's five miles from here.
We'd need a five-mile hose!

212
00:20:15,965 --> 00:20:17,966
- Where's this lake?
- That way.

213
00:20:26,601 --> 00:20:27,768
Tell them it's hopeless.

214
00:20:27,936 --> 00:20:30,354
You told me we had
an adequate water supply.

215
00:21:31,541 --> 00:21:32,541
Water!

216
00:21:47,724 --> 00:21:49,725
I tell you, that man's a miracle!

217
00:22:15,585 --> 00:22:18,086
Carol, you got gorgeous!

218
00:22:29,599 --> 00:22:31,224
Look at you.

219
00:22:39,525 --> 00:22:42,736
That was against Mid-City.
I'll never forget it.

220
00:22:44,113 --> 00:22:45,906
Fourth quarter, score was tied...

221
00:22:46,574 --> 00:22:48,784
we're back at the 25-yard line.

222
00:22:49,077 --> 00:22:52,287
Coach sends in a play,
Right Flanker Option.

223
00:23:02,215 --> 00:23:04,424
You really have grown, Clark.

224
00:23:04,592 --> 00:23:06,468
You look very well, Miss Bannister.

225
00:23:06,636 --> 00:23:11,431
I can't complain. I take the stairs
a little slow and I have these spells.

226
00:23:12,225 --> 00:23:14,142
But really, I can't complain.

227
00:23:15,061 --> 00:23:16,103
Lana?

228
00:23:17,271 --> 00:23:18,313
Clark?

229
00:23:23,903 --> 00:23:27,489
Would you excuse me? There's someone
I'd really like to say hello to.

230
00:23:30,827 --> 00:23:32,077
Lana?

231
00:23:33,454 --> 00:23:36,623
- Lana Lang? It's great to see you.
- Clark.

232
00:23:37,959 --> 00:23:41,336
- You look wonderful.
- Me? No, you look...

233
00:23:41,546 --> 00:23:44,548
- Let me give you a hand with that.
- No, no. I can manage.

234
00:23:48,052 --> 00:23:51,304
This is the first time you've come back
since your mom passed away.

235
00:23:51,514 --> 00:23:53,348
Yeah. I'm sorry.

236
00:23:56,352 --> 00:23:57,519
I heard that you and...

237
00:23:58,479 --> 00:24:00,814
- Donald split up.
- Did you eat yet?

238
00:24:01,023 --> 00:24:02,065
No.

239
00:24:02,358 --> 00:24:05,068
Beg your pardon. Excuse me. Sorry.

240
00:24:08,865 --> 00:24:10,699
- That's not right.
- No?

241
00:24:10,867 --> 00:24:13,368
You're right about Donald and me,
but... Hold this, okay?

242
00:24:13,578 --> 00:24:14,953
Oh, sure.

243
00:24:17,373 --> 00:24:18,874
Hi, Kent.

244
00:24:19,208 --> 00:24:21,501
Hi. How you doing?

245
00:24:22,712 --> 00:24:25,005
I'm sorry. I'm going nuts. Thanks.

246
00:24:28,885 --> 00:24:30,844
- Clark.
- Yeah.

247
00:24:31,721 --> 00:24:33,221
Lana.

248
00:24:36,225 --> 00:24:37,392
Hey, sweet.

249
00:24:37,727 --> 00:24:38,894
Here I am.

250
00:24:40,104 --> 00:24:44,232
Remember when you were prom queen?
All these guys were waiting for a dance?

251
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:47,068
There's only one guy on your
dance card now. Huh, honey?

252
00:24:47,236 --> 00:24:49,112
- That's good old...
- Brad Wilson.

253
00:24:49,697 --> 00:24:52,157
- Hi, Brad.
- Hi, Kent.

254
00:24:52,492 --> 00:24:54,242
Long time no see.

255
00:24:54,410 --> 00:24:56,328
You know, see, see, see?

256
00:24:56,996 --> 00:24:59,539
- Come on, Lana.
- No, I can't.

257
00:24:59,916 --> 00:25:01,875
- Clark already asked me.
- I did?

258
00:25:02,043 --> 00:25:03,877
- Yeah.
- Oh, excuse me.

259
00:25:05,004 --> 00:25:06,880
Lana, I haven't danced...

260
00:25:51,676 --> 00:25:54,469
Ah, Gorman.
Another week, another check.

261
00:25:57,390 --> 00:26:01,309
Don't you have another one for me?
I put in a voucher for expenses.

262
00:26:01,477 --> 00:26:02,811
What?

263
00:26:06,148 --> 00:26:07,190
Yeah, yeah.

264
00:26:07,483 --> 00:26:08,692
Here you go.

265
00:26:31,340 --> 00:26:33,091
Thanks for helping me out.

266
00:26:33,426 --> 00:26:36,011
You kidding? A lot of guys
would like to be where I am.

267
00:26:36,220 --> 00:26:38,638
You'd be surprised at how many
offers I didn't get.

268
00:26:38,806 --> 00:26:40,515
Even Brad wouldn't stick around.

269
00:26:40,725 --> 00:26:42,183
It really isn't easy.

270
00:26:42,351 --> 00:26:44,352
The streamers?
Yeah, you just pull, and...

271
00:26:44,520 --> 00:26:47,022
No, not the streamers. Everything.

272
00:26:47,231 --> 00:26:49,524
Not that I'm complaining.
It's just that...

273
00:26:49,775 --> 00:26:52,694
I don't know why,
I just feel like I can talk to you.

274
00:26:52,862 --> 00:26:53,987
What?

275
00:26:54,155 --> 00:26:56,489
I feel like I can talk to you!

276
00:26:57,450 --> 00:26:59,034
- You can?
- Yes.

277
00:26:59,243 --> 00:27:01,202
- You know something, Lana?
- What?

278
00:27:03,247 --> 00:27:04,539
I always...

279
00:27:05,333 --> 00:27:07,042
I always wished that you would.

280
00:27:07,251 --> 00:27:09,210
I mean, even back in high school.

281
00:27:09,378 --> 00:27:12,047
- Remember when you were?
- Queen of the prom.

282
00:27:12,632 --> 00:27:15,675
Then three years after the royal wedding,
the king abdicated.

283
00:27:15,885 --> 00:27:18,053
- Isn't that terrible?
- Yeah, sure is.

284
00:27:18,220 --> 00:27:22,057
There must be a gallon
of potato salad left over.

285
00:27:22,683 --> 00:27:24,559
You know what the problem is?

286
00:27:25,686 --> 00:27:27,562
I don't know, too much mayonnaise?

287
00:27:27,772 --> 00:27:30,523
Donald loved mayonnaise.
Why would that be the problem?

288
00:27:30,733 --> 00:27:33,568
No, the problem is,
why do I stay in Smallville?

289
00:27:33,778 --> 00:27:35,528
Believe me, I've asked myself that.

290
00:27:35,780 --> 00:27:40,241
Do you know how lucky you are
to live in Metropolis? The Big Apricot.

291
00:27:40,409 --> 00:27:41,660
Well, Lana, you could...

292
00:27:41,827 --> 00:27:44,579
Easy to say. But how?
What about Ricky?

293
00:27:44,830 --> 00:27:47,165
- Ricky?
- My little boy.

294
00:27:47,583 --> 00:27:49,709
- You? Oh, that's great.
- Yeah.

295
00:27:49,919 --> 00:27:54,422
I mean, at least here we have a house
and I've got a job that pays the bills.

296
00:27:54,590 --> 00:27:58,093
Except for last winter when
the fuel bills kept going up and up.

297
00:27:58,803 --> 00:28:01,596
Yeah. Even had to pawn
my diamond ring then.

298
00:28:01,931 --> 00:28:03,223
That's a shame.

299
00:28:10,940 --> 00:28:12,607
You never got married?

300
00:28:14,694 --> 00:28:16,319
- Me?
- Yeah.

301
00:28:16,821 --> 00:28:18,279
Well, I was...

302
00:28:19,740 --> 00:28:21,282
No. Not...

303
00:28:30,459 --> 00:28:33,336
You know, years later you can
look at someone and think...

304
00:28:33,587 --> 00:28:36,339
"Well, I guess that's
the one that got away".

305
00:28:41,220 --> 00:28:44,806
Give me that again, old buddy.
Run it by me just one more time.

306
00:28:44,974 --> 00:28:47,475
- Eighty-five thousand dollars.
- Missing?

307
00:28:47,643 --> 00:28:51,229
Embezzled, Mr. Webster.
Stolen from the firm.

308
00:28:51,439 --> 00:28:52,647
By whom?

309
00:28:52,857 --> 00:28:55,358
That's what I want to know.
By whom? Whom?

310
00:28:55,568 --> 00:28:57,152
Vera, get a hold of yourself.

311
00:28:58,070 --> 00:28:59,446
Nobody else ever will.

312
00:29:00,156 --> 00:29:01,322
I don't know.

313
00:29:01,490 --> 00:29:02,490
Whom?

314
00:29:02,658 --> 00:29:04,826
In the old days it was simple.

315
00:29:04,994 --> 00:29:09,372
We kept books, we knew what was
going in and what was paid out.

316
00:29:09,582 --> 00:29:11,249
If somebody wanted to rob you...

317
00:29:11,417 --> 00:29:13,960
they'd come in with a gun and say,
"Stick them up".

318
00:29:14,170 --> 00:29:17,297
Now they get blasted computers
to do their dirty work.

319
00:29:17,882 --> 00:29:20,759
My old friend, you are yesterday.

320
00:29:20,968 --> 00:29:23,845
Whoever pulled this caper is tomorrow.

321
00:29:25,973 --> 00:29:28,141
Mr. Webster,
it's time for your massage.

322
00:29:28,309 --> 00:29:30,185
Does this woman
have the right to burst in?

323
00:29:30,394 --> 00:29:33,980
Now, now, Vera. Simpson,
you know my psychic nutritionist?

324
00:29:34,190 --> 00:29:38,318
- Hello.
- We are trying to hold a meeting here.

325
00:29:38,486 --> 00:29:42,530
Why don't you hold your breath instead.
Maybe you'll turn blue.

326
00:29:42,698 --> 00:29:46,034
- Improvement.
- I'm about to take a human life.

327
00:29:46,202 --> 00:29:49,412
Simpson, would you excuse us
for a second, please?

328
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:56,044
- Mouths closed. Ears open.
- She's a big pig.

329
00:29:56,212 --> 00:29:59,339
I can't have anyone with me
who isn't with me.

330
00:29:59,673 --> 00:30:01,049
Now, girls.

331
00:30:01,509 --> 00:30:03,009
Simpson.

332
00:30:03,344 --> 00:30:04,719
Well, old chum. What now?

333
00:30:04,970 --> 00:30:07,680
Kiss the 85 thou goodbye?

334
00:30:07,890 --> 00:30:11,684
Keep on paying the thief his salary
until he shakes the money tree again?

335
00:30:11,894 --> 00:30:14,979
- He's bound to slip up sooner or later.
- Why?

336
00:30:15,189 --> 00:30:17,524
That's what they always say
in the movies.

337
00:30:17,733 --> 00:30:20,235
He won't slip up at all. No, not at all.

338
00:30:20,444 --> 00:30:23,071
He'll keep quietly taking
the bread from our mouths.

339
00:30:23,239 --> 00:30:27,492
He'll keep a low profile and won't
do a thing to call attention to himself.

340
00:30:27,701 --> 00:30:32,080
Unless, of course, he is
a complete and utter moron.

341
00:30:49,723 --> 00:30:51,474
I'll go first. Andrew.

342
00:30:51,684 --> 00:30:55,103
- I'll pick Chris.
- You feel good? You feel ready?

343
00:30:55,354 --> 00:30:56,604
LANA
Ricky, your shoe.

344
00:30:56,772 --> 00:31:00,108
- You mean, we've gotta take Ricky?
- You guys lost the toss.

345
00:31:00,276 --> 00:31:02,443
All right, come on, Ricky.

346
00:31:02,611 --> 00:31:04,612
- Wait, wait...
- Come on, good luck.

347
00:31:05,739 --> 00:31:08,575
- I just can't stand this.
- Oh, Lana. It'll be okay.

348
00:31:08,784 --> 00:31:11,077
I know, I was a late bloomer myself.

349
00:31:11,287 --> 00:31:15,957
It's not just that he's small, he's
the only kid in town without a father.

350
00:31:16,375 --> 00:31:20,712
Oh, look. He's stewed to the gills
in the middle of the afternoon.

351
00:31:20,880 --> 00:31:23,089
- Gee, all he had was chocolate milk.
- No, him.

352
00:31:23,299 --> 00:31:24,757
Hey, sweet thing.

353
00:31:25,217 --> 00:31:27,135
Little kid getting hassled, huh?

354
00:31:27,803 --> 00:31:30,305
- Kent, you still here?
- I seem to be, Brad.

355
00:31:30,514 --> 00:31:33,224
All he needs is a few pointers
from the old champ here.

356
00:31:33,601 --> 00:31:36,269
I won the all-country bowling
trophy two years in a row.

357
00:31:36,437 --> 00:31:37,478
I didn't know that.

358
00:31:37,646 --> 00:31:39,606
Yeah. Natural athlete
can play any sport.

359
00:31:39,773 --> 00:31:41,566
Brad, you're just gonna
make it worse.

360
00:31:41,734 --> 00:31:44,235
- It's all right. It'll be okay.
- He'll make it worse.

361
00:31:50,576 --> 00:31:52,577
You watch, he'll get a spare.

362
00:31:52,828 --> 00:31:54,287
Come on, Ricky.

363
00:31:55,664 --> 00:31:57,540
Hey, kid, you're holding it all wrong.

364
00:31:58,125 --> 00:32:01,419
- Let old Brad show you how it's done.
- Brad.

365
00:32:02,338 --> 00:32:06,341
Excuse me. Say, Brad, I think maybe
he'll be better off doing it his way.

366
00:32:06,592 --> 00:32:10,136
For a guy lucky to be water boy,
you've got a big mouth.

367
00:32:10,554 --> 00:32:13,598
I don't think he needs a lesson
in front of the other kids.

368
00:32:13,807 --> 00:32:17,685
- He needs a man to show him.
- He's doing just fine. Excuse me.

369
00:32:19,563 --> 00:32:20,855
Here you go, Ricky.

370
00:32:21,065 --> 00:32:24,067
And give it your best shot.
Okay? There you go.

371
00:32:26,487 --> 00:32:27,695
Sorry.

372
00:32:34,203 --> 00:32:35,370
Ah-choo!

373
00:32:43,796 --> 00:32:45,213
Gesundheit.

374
00:32:45,381 --> 00:32:46,547
Thank you.

375
00:32:49,593 --> 00:32:51,844
Hey, Gus, the boss wants to see you.

376
00:32:52,054 --> 00:32:54,597
He can see me all right.
Hello, Mr. Lewis.

377
00:32:54,807 --> 00:32:58,226
No, not that boss. The boss.

378
00:32:59,395 --> 00:33:00,895
- You mean, the boss...
- Yup.

379
00:33:01,105 --> 00:33:02,563
- Wants to see me?
- Yup.

380
00:33:02,731 --> 00:33:05,900
Oh, my God,
why would he wanna see me?

381
00:33:06,110 --> 00:33:07,235
I mean...

382
00:33:08,570 --> 00:33:10,905
Why would the boss wanna see me?

383
00:33:12,157 --> 00:33:13,825
There's no reason.

384
00:33:15,119 --> 00:33:16,619
Then why'd he? Oh, I know!

385
00:33:16,829 --> 00:33:19,914
It's my suggestion
for the volleyball uniforms.

386
00:33:20,124 --> 00:33:21,332
That's it.

387
00:33:33,929 --> 00:33:37,140
Ross the boss.
Ross the boss. The boss!

388
00:33:38,058 --> 00:33:40,143
Be calm. Be cool. Be collected.

389
00:33:44,857 --> 00:33:47,859
Mr. Webster? Mr. Webster?

390
00:33:48,402 --> 00:33:51,696
Mr. Webster, I did not... Mr. Webster.

391
00:33:52,114 --> 00:33:54,115
Mr. August Gorman?

392
00:33:54,283 --> 00:33:55,533
August Gorman here.

393
00:33:55,743 --> 00:34:00,288
I know you're a man of compassion,
and I don't wanna go to jail...

394
00:34:00,456 --> 00:34:02,457
because they have robbers
and rapists...

395
00:34:02,666 --> 00:34:05,043
I just wanna ask you one question.

396
00:34:05,252 --> 00:34:07,962
You've been a naughty guy,
haven't you?

397
00:34:08,213 --> 00:34:09,630
Come on, admit it now.

398
00:34:09,798 --> 00:34:12,300
You've been just a little bit naughty,
haven't you?

399
00:34:12,551 --> 00:34:15,303
- I was kind of...
- That's all right. I understand.

400
00:34:15,471 --> 00:34:18,681
I can... What do
the young folks say today?

401
00:34:18,891 --> 00:34:21,559
"Dig where you're
coming from, brother".

402
00:34:21,769 --> 00:34:24,604
- You wanna be rich, right?
- How, what?

403
00:34:24,813 --> 00:34:28,316
I was born rich. Never worn
the same pair of socks twice.

404
00:34:28,484 --> 00:34:29,984
What do you do with your socks?

405
00:34:30,235 --> 00:34:34,113
I don't know. They're laundered and sent
to some charitable institution, I think.

406
00:34:34,323 --> 00:34:37,492
Actually, I don't know.
Maybe they turn them into dust rags...

407
00:34:37,701 --> 00:34:39,160
or pen-wipers or something.

408
00:34:39,328 --> 00:34:40,995
Or maybe socks.

409
00:34:41,205 --> 00:34:43,956
Yes! That never occurred to me.

410
00:34:44,166 --> 00:34:47,960
Gus, you know something?
You're a genius.

411
00:34:48,212 --> 00:34:51,839
A naughty genius, but what the hell?
Nobody's perfect, right? Cheers.

412
00:34:52,007 --> 00:34:55,009
Because of the half-cent thing
with the computers.

413
00:34:55,260 --> 00:34:58,179
No, no, because computers
rule the world today.

414
00:34:58,347 --> 00:35:02,016
The fellow that can fool the computers
can rule the world himself.

415
00:35:03,018 --> 00:35:06,521
I've been searching for somebody
who can make these machines...

416
00:35:06,688 --> 00:35:09,023
do what they're not supposed to.
Get my drift?

417
00:35:09,441 --> 00:35:11,150
- Yes!
- Gus...

418
00:35:11,318 --> 00:35:16,114
Webscoe, the Webscoe industrial
complex, is a family-owned cartel.

419
00:35:16,323 --> 00:35:18,199
Some magnesium here,
some zinc there.

420
00:35:18,367 --> 00:35:20,368
Railroads, farm machinery.
You follow me?

421
00:35:20,536 --> 00:35:22,036
I follow you, sir.

422
00:35:22,246 --> 00:35:24,372
- Gus, do you know what I want now?
- No.

423
00:35:24,540 --> 00:35:25,623
I want coffee.

424
00:35:25,791 --> 00:35:27,542
All right. Black, cream, sugar, or?

425
00:35:27,751 --> 00:35:29,794
No, you don't seem to understand.

426
00:35:30,003 --> 00:35:33,381
Under different company names,
I control the price of coffee beans...

427
00:35:33,632 --> 00:35:37,760
in Venezuela, Brazil, Bolivia,
Jamaica and the Republic of Gabon.

428
00:35:37,970 --> 00:35:41,722
But I've got a problem and I think
maybe you can help me.

429
00:35:41,890 --> 00:35:45,893
One country won't play ball with me.
You know how that can bug a guy, right?

430
00:35:46,061 --> 00:35:48,396
That could bug... What country?

431
00:35:49,773 --> 00:35:52,024
- Colombia.
- Colombia?

432
00:35:52,192 --> 00:35:55,194
Colombia has two important exports,
and one of them's coffee.

433
00:35:55,404 --> 00:35:59,031
And I've tried to reason with them.
Believe me, I've tried.

434
00:35:59,241 --> 00:36:02,368
But this one miserable,
pissant little country...

435
00:36:02,578 --> 00:36:07,915
has the gall to think it can dictate
the economy of an open market. Gus.

436
00:36:08,417 --> 00:36:10,751
Gus, my friend...

437
00:36:11,587 --> 00:36:14,380
we're going to teach them
a lesson, aren't we?

438
00:36:15,424 --> 00:36:18,259
Destroy the entire
Colombian coffee crop...

439
00:36:18,427 --> 00:36:20,928
right down to the last bean.

440
00:36:21,096 --> 00:36:23,389
- The last bean, we are.
- Right.

441
00:36:23,599 --> 00:36:26,934
But you got so much. You know, like...

442
00:36:27,102 --> 00:36:29,812
A wise man once said,
I think it was Attila the Hun...

443
00:36:30,022 --> 00:36:32,607
"It is not enough that I succeed.

444
00:36:32,816 --> 00:36:35,776
Everyone else must fail".

445
00:36:36,028 --> 00:36:37,528
Seems fair.

446
00:36:37,821 --> 00:36:39,280
- Gus.
- What?

447
00:36:39,448 --> 00:36:43,117
You are going to do this for me.

448
00:36:45,746 --> 00:36:47,914
- How?
- The weather.

449
00:36:48,624 --> 00:36:50,291
You didn't say your mother was here.

450
00:36:50,459 --> 00:36:53,461
I'm his sister. His baby sister.

451
00:36:53,629 --> 00:36:56,631
Gus, tell me, have you ever
heard of Vulcan?

452
00:36:56,965 --> 00:36:58,299
Hi, Ms. Vulcan.

453
00:36:58,467 --> 00:37:01,260
Vulcan is the weather satellite
our government put up...

454
00:37:01,470 --> 00:37:02,803
to monitor the weather.

455
00:37:02,971 --> 00:37:07,266
But if somebody were to reprogram it,
it could do much more.

456
00:37:07,476 --> 00:37:09,101
It could make weather.

457
00:37:09,269 --> 00:37:10,811
Storms and floods.

458
00:37:10,979 --> 00:37:12,772
Blizzards, heat waves.

459
00:37:12,981 --> 00:37:14,148
How do you do that?

460
00:37:14,566 --> 00:37:17,818
Like everything else
in the 20th century, Gus.

461
00:37:17,986 --> 00:37:19,487
You push buttons.

462
00:37:21,156 --> 00:37:24,367
- There you go.
- It's the first time I won anything.

463
00:37:24,576 --> 00:37:25,826
You won my hand, Maury.

464
00:37:25,994 --> 00:37:28,829
But this is the first time
I won anything valuable.

465
00:37:28,997 --> 00:37:30,665
Let's get one with the sombreros.

466
00:37:30,874 --> 00:37:34,168
Mr. White, you'll be in this,
handing them their plane tickets.

467
00:37:34,378 --> 00:37:36,837
- Why do I have to do this?
- Why do I have to do this?

468
00:37:37,005 --> 00:37:40,341
You're lucky I didn't fire you.
I get a chance at exclusive photos...

469
00:37:40,509 --> 00:37:42,343
of history's biggest factory fire.

470
00:37:42,511 --> 00:37:45,346
He comes home with a broken leg
and 12 melted rolls of film.

471
00:37:45,514 --> 00:37:46,847
It was hot.

472
00:37:47,015 --> 00:37:49,183
Smile, Mr. White.

473
00:37:50,185 --> 00:37:52,770
South America!
I can't believe my luck!

474
00:37:53,272 --> 00:37:56,190
See, if you don't want them
to trace it back...

475
00:37:56,400 --> 00:37:59,527
you've gotta punch in
to some little rinky-dink outfit...

476
00:37:59,695 --> 00:38:02,154
that has a little
Mickey Mouse computer...

477
00:38:02,364 --> 00:38:05,324
Some place you can sneak into, right?

478
00:38:05,534 --> 00:38:06,701
Somebody could...

479
00:38:06,910 --> 00:38:10,913
Some place where nobody knows him
so they can't connect him with us.

480
00:38:11,123 --> 00:38:13,040
Webscoe has 112 subsidiaries.

481
00:38:13,292 --> 00:38:16,210
They're all linked into
the central computer system.

482
00:38:16,461 --> 00:38:18,045
